expand_less
[sshd]
enabled = true
port = 53222
ignoreip = 127.0.0.1/8 192.168.0.0/16 10.0.0.0/8

2. Legacy Watchtower Labeling

Location: Phase 7 (Step 1 & 2) – DuckDNS and NPM Docker Compose

Issue: The guide utilizes the label com.centurylinklabs.watchtower.enable=true. While functional for backward compatibility, CenturyLink Labs no longer maintains Watchtower; it is now maintained by containrrr.

Fix / Resolution: While optional, updating the label to the modern standard ensures future-proofing, though the current configuration executes perfectly.

🛡️ SYSTEM STATE & LOGICAL FLOW VERIFICATION

Atomic Package Management: The execution of rpm-ostree override remove podman-docker --install docker-ce... (Phase 3) is executed perfectly as a single atomic transaction. This prevents dependency resolution conflicts that occur if a user tries to layer Docker CE while the Bazzite Podman shim is actively present.

SELinux Bootstrapping: The guide correctly identifies that semanage (via policycoreutils-python-utils) must be layered and rebooted before SSH is configured (Phase 4), otherwise the sshd bind to 53222 will be silently murdered by the kernel. The logic here is sequentially flawless.

Storage Labeling Integrity: The warning in Phase 6 regarding mount order vs. restorecon execution is a masterclass in SELinux extended attribute (xattr) behavior. Restoring context on an empty directory, mounting over it, and subsequently getting permission denied errors is a notorious container trap. The guide perfectly navigates this.

Docker Network Isolation: Setting APACHE_IP_BINDING=127.0.0.1 inside a container while allowing NPM to route via the nextcloud-aio internal bridge network is functionally correct. It isolates the Nextcloud UI from host-level network exposure while allowing container-to-container routing via Docker's embedded DNS.

Session Management Logic: The validation pipeline using loginctl show-session -p Seat inside an awk loop reliably isolates the physical display (seat0) status. This prevents the scripts from misidentifying the user's virtual TTY SSH session as a graphical blocker.

✅ FINAL VALIDATION CHECKLIST

To prove the system has reached the intended end state deterministically, the following verifiable outputs must be achieved:

System Boot State: Power cycling the server results in a black screen or SDDM idle login screen. loginctl list-sessions returns empty or only virtual SSH TTYs.

Network Security: Running ss -tlnp | grep sshd on the server returns listening status only on port 53222. Port 22 connections must time out.

Session Transitions:

Executing ssh -p 53222 user@ip 'sudo start-kde.sh' causes the physical display to output the KDE Plasma desktop within 5 seconds.

Executing ssh -p 53222 user@ip 'sudo start-gaming.sh' while KDE is running returns ERROR: A graphical session is already active and aborts safely.

Logging out via the physical KDE desktop interface correctly returns the system to the headless SDDM idle state (verified by ls /etc/sddm.conf.d/ showing only zzz-headless-server.conf).

Data Isolation: ls -Z /srv/nextcloud-data outputs system_u:object_r:container_file_t:s0, proving the SELinux policy allows confined Docker containers to read/write the host directory.

Remote Desktop Integrity: RDP connection to the server's LAN IP on port 3389 fails (blocked by firewalld), but succeeds when connecting to localhost:3389 while the SSH tunnel is active.

